did.unittitle: Video Free Earth Production Company records
did.abstract: Collection contains videos, production files, general business files, personal and business correspondence, scripts, photographs, slides, and negatives. The material dates from 1983-89. The collection documents the work of late gay artist Jamie Walters.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition note
acqinfo.p: The Video Free Earth Production Company Collection was donated to the Gelman Library in 1996 by Mr. Kenneth Rothschild and Mr. Leonard Braverman. It is part of the Gay and Lesbian History Archives of the Special Collections Department.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized in two series: Leonard Braverman papers, and Kenneth Rothschild papers.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Video Free Earth Production Company was founded in 1982 as a broadcast and commercial videotape company, and the collection chronicles video work of Washington, D.C. dramatic and performance artists. The company was co-founded by Jamie Walters and Leonard Braverman.

prefercite.head: Preferred citation
prefercite.p: Video Free Earth Production Company records, Special Collections Research Center, The George Washington University.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The collection contains videos, production files, general business files, personal and business correspondence, scripts, photographs, slides, and negatives. The material dates from 1983-89. The collection documents the work of late gay artist Jamie Walters. Walters scripted, directed, and performed numerous satirical pieces designed for video. His work was exhibited in a number of galleries, including the Tate Gallery in London. The collection documents the innovative development and exploration of video to produce artwork.

userestrict.head: Restrictions on Use
userestrict.p: Some material may be copyrighted or restricted. It is the patron's obligation to determine and satisfy copyright or other case restrictions when publishing or otherwise distributing materials found in the collections.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This finding aid was revised in 2022 to address derogatory descriptive language. During that revision, description was not edited or removed, but additional information was provided to add context. The Historic Context note for this archival object explains the revision Videotapes: Compilation Tape no. 5 - 1 cassette (VHS). View the Pre-revision Feb. 2022 finding aid of Video Free Earth Production Company records to see the description prior to the revision.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series consists of videotapes, photographs, and printed material. The years cover 1971-90. These include performance poetry by Chasen Gaver, and satirical looks at Joan Kennedy (ex-wife of Senator Ted Kennedy), D.C. Mayor Marion Barry. A number of other social and political topics are lampooned. The printed material consists of production files, public relations files, photographs, and some oversized items (mostly 11x14" photographs). The production files deal with the various films made by Video Free Earth, and include scripts, editing logs, story boards, correspondence, resum√©s, newspaper clippings, grant applications, and budgets. Many of these videos were written and directed by Jamie Walters, the co-founder of the company along with Mr. Braverman.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: [From original finding aid]: master with titles; Feb. 1986; 2:35 min. (NOTE: also on Video Salon I Tape, Compilation Tape no. 3, and Mayor's Show). By Chasen Gaver; directed by Jamie Walters; video by Leonard Braverman. This is Gaver's punk poem about the battle of the human spirit against the story waves of life. As Gaver points out, "some people miss the boat."

odd.head: General note
odd.p: [From original finding aid]: c. 41 min.; master. First Lady Joan (NOTE: also on Compilation Tapes no. 5 and 6, Jamie Walters Retrospective and Performance Pastiche). By Jamie Walters; with Jamie Walters and Jack Guidone1980; c.28 min. A parody of American domestic and political life. Barbara Walters interviews Joan Kennedy. Assuming a reconciliation with Ted this acerbic farce casts alcoholic, manic depressive Joan Kennedy as first lady. First segment of "A Kennedy Trilogy." Joan Comes Home (NOTE: also on Compilation Tape no. 5 and 6, Jamie Walters Retrospective). Directed by David Vanderbilt; written by Jamie Walters 1980; 5 min. In this abrasive concluding segment of "A Kennedy Trilogy," Joan returns to the White House after hospital treatment. Jackie Strikes Back (NOTE: also on Compilation Tapes no. 5 and 6, Jamie Walters Retrospective). Directed by Jamie Walters; written by Chasen Gaver 1982; 7 min. A spoof on Jacqueline Onassis's possible telephone response to First Lady Joan. Second segment of "A Kennedy Trilogy."

odd.head: General note
odd.p: [From original finding aid]: on container label: 1; contains the following: Baja Fantasy (NOTE: also on Compilation Tape no. 9). Directed and written by Jamie Walters; music by Flaco Jimenez 1984; 4 min. An exciting juxtaposition of ideas, where we discover daydreaming or reality. A visual and musical interpretation of a dream about yearning to return to a distant "mental oasis." Film from the Mexican Baja is blended with video of a young man reading, showering and doing garden chores. Beat (description in Series I, Tape 8). The Bike Pants Phenomenon (description in Series I, Tape 9). The Boat (description in Series I, Tape 10). Capitol Hill - 1982; c. 6 min. (NOTE: also on Compilation Tapes no. 6 and 8, and Jamie Walters Retrospective). Directed by Jamie Walters; written by Joseph Lanz. Details the daily trials of a depressed Republican Senate aide, who struggles to work and is wronged by life at every turn. Cuckoo Clock (description in Series I, Tape 22). Crack Politician (description in Series I, Tape 20). Desk in Hell (description in Series I, Tape 23)

odd.head: General note
odd.p: [From original finding aid]: on container label: 3 First Lady Joan (description in Series I, Tape 11). Joan Comes Home (description in Series I, Tape 11). Jackie Strikes Back (description in Series I, Tape 11). First Lady Joan-The Remake Directed by Leonard Braverman; written by Jamie Walters; 12 min.1982. Remake of 1980 version. Fresh Out of Ideas (NOTE: also on Compilation Tape no. 9). By Jamie Walters and Chasen Gaver 1984; 2 min. Gaver is an actor rather than a reciter and pulls the "text" out of a gold-leaf skull, folds it into an airplane and then tosses it over and over. Scenes of newspaper production and World War II propaganda footage are intercut with this main action, echoing visually the rhythms of the poem. Gloria's Point of View (NOTE: also on Compilation Tape no. 6). Directed and written by Jamie Walters 1984; 4 min. A satiric commentary of the media overkill that pervades our society. Gloria Vanderbilt reacts to Ronald Reagan's "Star Wars" speech as she has tea. Litany of Addresses (NOTE: also on Video Salon I and on Compilation tape no. 5; detailed description in Series I, Tape 56) By Isabel-Lee Malone; directed by Jamie Walters; 13 min.1987. Les Femmes Perdues Louise Nevelson Takes a Bath (NOTE: also on Compilation Tape no. 8). Directed and written by Jamie Walters 1983; 3:30 min. Louise Nevelson is here portrayed as a droll transvestite. The sculptor discusses her life and perspectives on her work. Preparation H (description in Series I, Tape 38)

processinfo.head: Historic Context note
processinfo.p: The term transvestite used in the General note for this item is from the original description and likely generated by the creator of the materials. It is often historically relevant to know what terminology was used by the creator of archives. For this reason SCRC staff did not remove or edit the description.

The term transvestite is identified as derogatory in the resource Homosaurs.org. Homosaurus is an international linked data vocabulary of Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer (LGBTQ) terms. Louise Nevelson was an American sculptor known for her monumental, monochromatic, wooden wall pieces and outdoor sculptures and for questioning femininity in art.
View the Pre-revision Feb. 2022 finding aid of Video Free Earth Production Company records to see the description prior to the revision.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: [From original finding aid]: c. 54:12 min.; credits: executive producer, Margot Kernan; Bob Boilen, Christine Graham, Margot Kernan, Jamie Walters, Nancy Garruba, Garri Garripoli; features five stories of childhood: Cuckoo Clock; Gina's Dream By Christine Graham. Uses oversized papier mache figures to represent things in life that preoccupy us, such as money. Young Gina breaks the bonds and starts on the path to individuality; Hiding By Margot Kernan. A series of sepia-tinted still photographs projected on the video monitor while Kernan reads a narrative poem about a young woman's loss of innocence at her grandmother's house when she catches her with the gardener; St. Lucy and the Pagans By Nancy Garruba. A wacky swack at Catholic guilt. As Lucy dresses to go to an official function with her husband, she tells the tale of why she quit Catholic school; Picture Parents By Garri Garripoli. Examines the influence of television on the young mind of Peter Hubbard and the parental abilities of Dan Dowdall and Terr Nussbaumer
